  "opinion": "As a woman who grew up in a household where both parents were PhDs but now works as a barista in New York, I’ve seen firsthand how the gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about who gets to dream big. My parents’ academic backgrounds shaped my early curiosity, but their emphasis on practical problem-solving over theoretical abstraction left me questioning whether I could thrive in a field dominated by rigid, hierarchical structures. The gender gap in science isn’t merely a statistic; it’s the quiet discouragement I’ve felt when colleagues dismiss my ideas as 'too vague' or when I’m the only woman in a room full of engineers who’ve never even heard of me. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. Instead of top-down mandates, I believe we need grassroots change—like mentorship circles for women in STEM that start in high school, or community-based science outreach programs that bring coding and lab work to underserved neighborhoods. My own journey as a mother of three has taught me that support systems must be flexible and inclusive, not just for women but for all who face barriers. For instance, when I tried to explain quantum physics to my kids during our gardening sessions, they asked questions that made me realize how much more we can learn together. The key is to build bridges, not walls. We don’t need to fix science to be gender-neutral; we need to ensure that every person, regardless of background, feels empowered to contribute. This isn’t about changing the system—it’s about nurturing the next generation of scientists who see themselves reflected in the work they do.",
